04531nmm a2200661Ia 9789633863060DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20192019hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2019009664  a9789633863060  a(DE-B1597)633407  a(OCoLC)1338020175  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU10aD116.5 4aD116.5 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a943.7/02207202222300aTimes of Upheaval :bFour Medievalists in Twentieth-Century Central Europe. Conversations with Jerzy Kłoczowski, János M. Bak, František Šmahel, and Herwig Wolfram /ced. by Paweł Kras, Pavlína Rychterová, Gábor Klaniczay, Walter Pohl. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (396 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tIntroducing Jerzy Kłoczowski -- tJerzy Kłoczowski in Conversation with Paweł Kras -- tIntroducing János M. Bak -- tJános M. Bak in Conversation with Gábor Klaniczay -- tIntroducing František Šmahel -- tFrantišek Šmahel in Conversation with Pavlína Rychterová -- tIntroducing Herwig Wolfram -- tHerwig Wolfram in Conversation with Walter Pohl -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe volume unites conversations with four masters of Medieval Studies from east-central Europe: János Bak from Hungary, Jerzy Kłoczowski from Poland, František Šmahel from the Czech Republic, and Herwig Wolfram from Austria. The interviews, made by younger colleagues, reveal engaging life stories, with numerous observations, anecdotes and experiences. The four scholars grew up before and during the war, under Nazi occupation, emerged as young scholars in the difficult post-war period, and, for most of their careers worked in the shadow of the Iron Curtain, two of them spending most of their lifetimes under communist regimes. The conversations focus on ways in which open-minded young intellectuals became medieval historians under difficult circumstances, how they experienced the long shadows of totalitarian regimes with their acute sensitivity for historical change, and how their perceptions of the world around them reflected back on their approach to medieval history. The histories of their nations were broken, most of them ceased to exist and then were re-established during their lifetimes, came under foreign domination, were split up, or had their territories shifted. These changes affected these scholars' identities and patriotic feelings, and their present was reflected in the distant mirror of the medieval past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aMedievalistszEurope, CentralvBiography. 0aMedievalistszEurope, CentralvInterviews. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBiography, Central and Eatern Europe, Cold War, Communism, Fascism, Medieval.1 aKlaniczay, Gábor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKras, Paweł, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPohl, Walter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRychterová, Pavlína, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2019z978311078051240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633863060423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633863060/original  a978-3-11-078051-2  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles